Salesforce to DfCA integration

DfCA ingests Salesforce Event Monitoring Logs via the API connector. Salesforce logs export and download events through Event Monitoring Event Log Files. Detailed access to these logs may require Salesforce Event Monitoring capabilities, which are commonly provided through Salesforce Shield depending on the organisation’s Salesforce licensing.

Test Actions

Log into Defender and navigate to Cloud Apps > Connected Apps > App Connectors

Confirm Salesforce shows status "Connected" with a last-synced timestamp

Navigate to Cloud Apps > Activity Log, filter by App = Salesforce, and confirm events are present

In Salesforce, go to Setup > Apps > Connected Apps and confirm DfCA appears with OAuth scopes listed

Expected Outcome

Connector status is Connected with no errors

Salesforce events (logins, admin actions, API calls) appear in the Defender Activity Log within 60 minutes of occurring

DfCA is visible as an authorised connected app inside Salesforce



Login Event Monitoring

Every login attempt, successful or failed, browser or API, generates a log entry with source IP, timestamp, and login type. This data underpins almost every other detection. Reference: Salesforce Login History and DfCA login event filters.

Test Actions

Log into Salesforce successfully via browser with a test account.

Deliberately fail login 6 times with an incorrect password on the same account

Make a successful API authentication call via Postman or Salesforce CLI

Make a failed API authentication call using an invalid client secret

Check Setup > Users > Login History in Salesforce, confirm all four event types appear

Check Cloud Apps > Activity Log in Defender, filter by App = Salesforce, Activity = Login, confirm all events appear within 60 minutes

Confirm successful and failed events are distinguishable by a status/result field

Expected Outcome

All four event types (successful UI, failed UI, successful API, failed API) appear in both Salesforce Login History and Defender Activity Log

Each event shows: username, source IP, timestamp, login type, success/failure status



Geolocation and Impossible Travel Detection

DfCA maps every login IP to a physical location using its threat intelligence engine. If the same account logs in from two locations impossible to travel between in the elapsed time, an alert fires. Reference: DfCA Impossible Travel policy.

Test Actions

Confirm the Impossible Travel policy is Enabled and scoped to Salesforce in Defender

Using a VPN, log into Salesforce from a UK IP, then switch to a distant VPN exit node (e.g. US West Coast or Asia) and log in again within 15 minutes with the same test account

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered Impossible Travel alert

Click into the alert and review the detail

Expected Outcome

Alert fires showing both logins, both IPs, both geolocations, timestamps, and the calculated time/distance delta

Alert severity is High and notification is delivered to the configured recipient

All login events in the Activity Log show geolocation data (country, city) regardless of whether an alert fired



Suspicious IP Detection

DfCA checks login IPs against threat intelligence feeds flagging known Tor exit nodes, botnets, and malicious IP ranges. A successful login from a suspicious IP is more alarming than a failed one.

Test Actions

Confirm the Activity from Anonymous IP policy is Enabled in Defender and scoped to Salesforce

In a test Salesforce org, create a custom IP range, tag it as an anonymous proxy, log in from that IP. 

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert

In the Activity Log, click into any login event and confirm the IP Tags field is populated where applicable

Expected Outcome

Login from a Tor exit node or known risky IP generates a High severity alert

Alert contains: username, IP address, IP threat classification, geolocation, timestamp

Activity Log events show IP tag metadata (e.g. "Anonymous proxy", "Tor") on flagged events

Logins from named/trusted locations are not flagged



Suspicious User Agent Detection

Every browser or tool sends a User-Agent string identifying itself. Unexpected non-browser agents (Python scripts, curl) accessing Salesforce suggest automated data extraction using stolen credentials.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Suspicious User Agent custom policy is active in Defender

Using Postman or curl, make an authenticated API call to a Salesforce test org

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

In the Activity Log, locate the API call event and confirm the User Agent field shows the non-browser string

Expected Outcome

API calls from Postman, curl, or Python scripts trigger a Medium severity alert

Alert contains: username, user agent string, source IP, timestamp

Legitimate browser sessions (Chrome, Edge, Firefox) do not trigger the policy



Breakglass / Local Account Use

Breakglass accounts bypass SSO and authenticate directly against Salesforce. They should almost never be used. Any login must generate an immediate alert. See Salesforce breakglass account guidance.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Breakglass Account Login custom policy is active with breakglass usernames in the filter

Log into Salesforce using a breakglass account, coordinate with your team first

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

Confirm the alert notification was delivered to the security team

Expected Outcome

Any breakglass login generates a High severity alert with: username, source IP, geolocation, timestamp, login result

Event also appears in Salesforce Login History

Regular SSO user logins do not trigger this policy



Multiple Successive Failed Logins

Repeated failed logins against the same account indicate a brute force attack. DfCA's built-in policy tracks failure counts within a rolling time window. Reference: DfCA multiple failed login policy.

Test Actions

Confirm the Multiple Failed Login Attempts policy is Enabled and scoped to Salesforce, note the configured threshold

Enter incorrect passwords for a test account 10 times in a row within 5 minutes

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

Check Setup > Users > Login History in Salesforce to confirm all 10 failed attempts are recorded

Expected Outcome

Alert fires after the threshold number of consecutive failures

Alert shows: targeted username, source IP, failure count, time window, and timeline of attempts

Alert severity is High



Data Export and File Download Detection

Unusually large data exports in a session indicate potential data theft. DfCA's built-in Mass Download policy monitors for this. Salesforce logs export events via Event Log Files.

Test Actions

Confirm the Mass Download by a Single User policy is Enabled and scoped to Salesforce

In a Salesforce test org, run and export 15–20 reports to CSV in quick succession with a test account

Download 10+ file attachments from records in the same session

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

In the Activity Log, filter by Activity = Report Export / Download and confirm all events appear with record counts

Expected Outcome

Alert fires showing: username, number of exports, time window, source IP, and list of individual export events

Individual export events in the Activity Log show report name and record count

Single normal report exports do not trigger the policy



Bulk API Data Request Detection

Unexpected Salesforce Bulk API usage, especially from a regular user account rather than a known integration service account, may indicate data exfiltration.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Bulk API Data Request custom policy is active in Defender

Using Salesforce CLI (sf data bulk query) or Postman, run 6 bulk data queries against a test org within one hour using a test user account

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

In the Activity Log, filter for the test user and confirm all bulk API events are captured

Expected Outcomes

Alert fires after > 5 bulk API jobs within 1 hour by the same user

Alert shows: username, job count, time window, source IP, and objects queried.

Known integration service accounts can be excluded from the policy to reduce noise



Bulk Deletion Detection

Rapid mass deletion of records is either sabotage or a serious mistake. Reference: Salesforce record deletion and the Recycle Bin.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Bulk Deletion Operation custom policy is active in Defender

In a Salesforce sandbox, create 60 dummy Contact records with a test user, then delete all 60 within a few minutes

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

In the Activity Log, confirm all 60 delete events appear attributed to the test user

Expected Outcome

Alert fires when > 50 deletions occur within 30 minutes by a single user

Alert shows: username, deletion count, object type, time window, source IP

Alert fires whether deletion was done via UI or API

Individual record deletions (1–2 records) do not trigger the policy



New Account Creation Monitoring

Unauthorised account creation, especially admin accounts, is a common attacker persistence technique. All creation events are logged in the Salesforce Setup Audit Trail.

Test Actions

Confirm both SF - New Admin Account Created (High) and SF - Any New User Created (Medium) policies are active

In a test org, create a new user with the System Administrator profile

Create a second new user with a standard profile

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for two alerts, one High, one Medium

Check Setup > Security > Setup Audit Trail and confirm both creation events appear with creator details

Expected Outcome

System Administrator account creation triggers a High severity alert

Any user account creation triggers a Medium severity alert

Each alert shows: new username, profile/permissions assigned, who created it, timestamp

Setup Audit Trail confirms both events



Permission Modification Monitoring

Quietly adding permissions to one's own account is a classic privilege escalation technique. All Profile and Permission Set changes are logged in the Setup Audit Trail.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Permission Modification custom policy is active in Defender

In a test org: modify a Permission Set (add a permission), assign it to a test user, and change a test user's Profile to a more privileged one

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for triggered alerts within 60 minutes

Check Setup > Security > Setup Audit Trail, confirm all three changes appear with old value, new value, admin identity, and timestamp

Expected Outcome

Each change (Permission Set modified, Permission Set assigned, Profile changed) triggers a separate High severity alert

Alerts show: admin who made the change, user/object affected, old value → new value, timestamp

Salesforce Audit Trail and Defender alerts are consistent



Account Enable / Disable Monitoring

Re-enabling a former employee's account is a serious risk. Unexpected disabling could mean someone covering their tracks. Reference: Salesforce user deactivation best practices.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - User Account Enabled/Disabled policy is active in Defender

In a test org, deactivate a test user account, then reactivate it

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for two alerts, Medium (deactivate), High (reactivate)

Check Salesforce Setup Audit Trail for both events with admin identity and timestamp

Expected Outcome

Deactivating a user triggers a Medium severity alert

Reactivating a user triggers a High severity alert

Each alert shows: admin who acted, affected username, action taken, timestamp



MFA Disabled on Account

Removing MFA from an account makes it trivially easier to compromise. Any instance must be investigated immediately. Reference: Salesforce MFA requirement.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - MFA Disabled on Account policy is active in Defender

In a test org, navigate to Setup > Identity > Identity Verification and exempt a test user from MFA

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a triggered alert within 60 minutes

Check Salesforce Setup Audit Trail for the MFA change entry

Re-enable MFA on the test account and confirm a second audit entry appears

Expected Outcome

Removing MFA from any user generates a High severity alert with: admin who changed it, affected user, nature of change, timestamp

Alert notification delivered to security team email

Audit Trail confirms the change consistently



Audit Logging Disabled

An attacker disabling audit logging is trying to operate undetected. This is one of the most critical events to catch. Reference: Salesforce Event Monitoring and DfCA anomaly detection.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Audit Logging Config Changed policy is active with Critical severity

In a test org, modify a debug log setting under Setup > Environments > Monitoring > Debug Logs, this creates an audit trail entry without disabling core logging

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for a Critical alert within 60 minutes

Confirm the alert notification was delivered and the Salesforce Setup Audit Trail captured the change

Expected Outcome

Any modification to audit or logging configuration triggers a Critical severity alert delivered rapidly

Setup Audit Trail confirms the change with admin identity and timestamp

Policy errs toward false positives, better to over-alert than miss a real attempt



Security Policy Changes (OWD, Sessions, Passwords, IP Restrictions)

Changes to sharing settings, session timeouts, password policies, and IP restrictions can weaken the entire Salesforce security posture instantly. OWD changes are especially dangerous, a single change can expose data to every user in the org.

Test Actions

Confirm the SF - Security Policy Changed policy is active in Defender

In a test org, make and then revert each of the following:

Setup > Security > Sharing Settings, change an OWD setting

Setup > Security > Session Settings, change the session timeout value

Setup > Security > Password Policies, change minimum password length

Check Cloud Apps > Alerts for three separate alerts within 60 minutes

Check Salesforce Setup Audit Trail, confirm all three changes appear with before/after values

Expected Outcome

Each setting change generates a separate High severity alert showing: admin, setting affected, old value → new value, timestamp

Reverting a change also generates an alert, full change history is visible

Audit Trail and Defender alerts are consistent with each other



